---
import DocsLayout from "../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";
import CodeTabs from "../../../components/CodeTabs.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="GDPR Operations">
  <h1>GDPR Operations</h1>
  <p>
    EntDB ships with first-class GDPR primitives on the Python SDK. Every
    operation is routed through the WAL, so each one is captured in the
    compliance audit trail.
  </p>

  <h2>user_id vs tenant_principal</h2>
  <p>
    GDPR operations are scoped by the <strong>global</strong>
    <code>user_id</code> (e.g. <code>"alice"</code>), not by the
    tenant-scoped <code>tenant_principal</code> (e.g.
    <code>"user:alice"</code>). A single user may exist as a principal
    across many tenants, and GDPR rights apply across all of them at once.
  </p>

  <h2>Subject Field</h2>
  <p>
    GDPR rights apply to data <em>about</em> a person, not data <em>created
    by</em> a person. EntDB needs to know which field on a node identifies
    the data subject. Declare it in your <code>.proto</code>:
  </p>
  <Code code={`message User {
  option (entdb.node) = {
    type_id: 1
    data_policy: DATA_POLICY_PERSONAL
    subject_field: "id"          // <-- this field identifies WHO the data is about
  };

  string id    = 1 [(entdb.field).required = true];
  string email = 2 [(entdb.field).pii = true];
  string name  = 3 [(entdb.field).pii = true];
}

message Comment {
  option (entdb.node) = {
    type_id: 2
    data_policy: DATA_POLICY_BUSINESS
    subject_field: "author_id"   // comments are "about" their author
  };

  string author_id = 1;
  string body      = 2;
}`} lang="proto" />
  <p>
    When <code>delete_user("alice")</code> runs, the server scans every node
    type that declares a <code>subject_field</code> and finds the rows whose
    subject field equals <code>"alice"</code>. The per-type
    <code>data_policy</code> then decides whether each row is hard-deleted,
    anonymized, or retained.
  </p>

  <h2>Data Policies</h2>
  <p>
    Each node type carries a <code>DataPolicy</code> classification (default:
    <code>PERSONAL</code>) that drives erase and export behaviour. The enum
    is defined in <code>proto/entdb_options.proto</code> and runtime
    semantics live in <code>dbaas/entdb_server/data_policy.py</code>.
  </p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Policy</th><th>On <code>delete_user</code></th><th>On <code>export_user_data</code></th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    <tr><td><code>PERSONAL</code> (default)</td><td>DELETE rows where subject = user</td><td>Fully exportable</td><td>The strictest default; what you want for user-owned content.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>BUSINESS</code></td><td>ANONYMIZE PII fields, keep row</td><td>User's own contributions exportable</td><td>Comments, posts, anything that has business value beyond the author.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>FINANCIAL</code></td><td>RETAIN row, ANONYMIZE PII</td><td>Exportable</td><td>Requires a documented <code>legal_basis</code> on the type.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>AUDIT</code></td><td>RETAIN row, ANONYMIZE PII</td><td>NOT user-exportable</td><td>Security/audit logs. Requires <code>legal_basis</code>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>EPHEMERAL</code></td><td>DELETE</td><td>Not exportable</td><td>Sessions, drafts, anything intentionally short-lived.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>HEALTHCARE</code></td><td>RETAIN row, ANONYMIZE PHI</td><td>Exportable</td><td>Field-level encryption for fields marked <code>phi: true</code>; 6-year retention default. Requires <code>legal_basis</code>.</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p>
    Fields marked
    <code>(entdb.field).pii = true</code> (or
    <code>phi = true</code> for healthcare) are the ones that get scrubbed
    when a policy says "anonymize". Non-PII fields stay intact so the row
    remains useful for the business.
  </p>

  <h2>Right-to-Erasure (delete_user)</h2>
  <p>
    Schedules a user for deletion with a configurable grace window. During
    the grace window the delete is reversible; after the window, a
    background worker walks every tenant the user touched and applies the
    per-type <code>data_policy</code> rules.
  </p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`result = await db.delete_user(
    "alice",
    actor="user:alice",      # who initiated (defaults to user:<user_id>)
    grace_days=30,
)
print(result["status"], result["execute_at"])`}
    goNote="GDPR delete_user is not yet exposed in the Go SDK. Call it from Python (or invoke the gRPC method directly) until the Go binding lands."
  />
  <p>What actually happens at the end of the grace window:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Erased</strong>: every row whose <code>subject_field</code>
      equals <code>"alice"</code> on a <code>PERSONAL</code> or
      <code>EPHEMERAL</code> type is hard-deleted.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Anonymized</strong>: rows on <code>BUSINESS</code>,
      <code>FINANCIAL</code>, <code>AUDIT</code>, or
      <code>HEALTHCARE</code> types keep their structure but every
      <code>pii: true</code> / <code>phi: true</code> field is replaced
      with a tombstone (e.g. "Deleted User"). Comments, orders, audit
      events that referenced Alice still point at the anonymized row.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Personal tenants dropped</strong>: a tenant where the user is
      the sole member is removed entirely.
    </li>
    <li>
      The deletion event itself is appended to the WAL &mdash; the audit
      trail records who triggered it, when, and the resolved policy per
      type.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Cancellation Window</h2>
  <p>
    Until <code>execute_at</code>, the deletion is reversible. After it
    fires, the per-type policies above run and there is no undo &mdash; the
    rows are gone (or anonymized irreversibly).
  </p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`# Within the grace window
await db.cancel_user_deletion("alice", actor="user:alice")

# Past execute_at: the request has already been processed and the
# data is gone. There is no rollback.`}
    goNote="cancel_user_deletion is not yet exposed in the Go SDK."
  />
  <p>
    Choose <code>grace_days</code> based on regulatory expectations and
    your support workflow. 30 days is the common default; 7 is the
    aggressive end; 0 means "execute immediately" (rare, usually only for
    administrative cleanup).
  </p>

  <h2>Right-to-Data-Portability (export_user_data)</h2>
  <p>
    Returns a structured snapshot of every node owned by or about the
    user, every ACL entry granted to them, and their tenant memberships.
    Use this to satisfy GDPR Articles 15 (access) and 20 (portability).
  </p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`bundle = await db.export_user_data("alice", actor="user:alice")

# bundle is a dict shaped roughly:
#   {
#     "user_id": "alice",
#     "tenants":           [...],   # tenant memberships
#     "owned_nodes":       [...],   # nodes Alice created
#     "shared_with_me":    [...],   # nodes shared TO Alice
#     "group_memberships": [...],
#   }`}
    goNote="export_user_data is not yet exposed in the Go SDK."
  />
  <p>
    What ends up in the bundle is determined by the per-type
    <code>data_policy</code>: <code>PERSONAL</code> and
    <code>BUSINESS</code> rows owned by Alice are included in full,
    <code>AUDIT</code> rows are <em>not</em> exportable, and
    <code>HEALTHCARE</code> rows include only the fields the user is
    permitted to receive. Deliver the bundle as a download link or
    encrypted email per your data-handling policy &mdash; the SDK leaves
    delivery to the application.
  </p>

  <h2>Freeze (Right-to-Object)</h2>
  <p>
    GDPR Article 18 lets a user demand processing be paused without their
    data being deleted. <code>freeze_user</code> sets a flag on the user
    that rejects all new writes by or about them; existing reads still
    succeed. Useful for legal hold, contested accounts, or pending
    erasure investigations.
  </p>
  <CodeTabs
    python={`# Freeze
await db.freeze_user("alice", enabled=True, actor="user:admin")

# Unfreeze (same call, enabled=False)
await db.freeze_user("alice", enabled=False, actor="user:admin")`}
    goNote="freeze_user is not yet exposed in the Go SDK."
  />
  <p>
    Freeze and erasure are independent: a frozen user can still be
    enrolled in <code>delete_user</code>, and an in-flight
    <code>delete_user</code> request can be cancelled even while the user
    is frozen.
  </p>

  <h2>Audit Trail</h2>
  <p>
    Each of these operations appends an event to the WAL with the actor who
    initiated it, the reason string, and the timestamp. When the WAL is
    backed by S3 with Object Lock, the record is tamper-evident.
  </p>
  <p>
    See <a href="/tenant-shard-db/docs/compliance/audit">Compliance &amp; Audit</a>
    for details on Object Lock, crypto-shred, and exporting the audit trail.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
